<br>
To go to a system such as FCFS/FFA is just a smoke screen to say that the few with more power (the so-called uber guilds) want more access than any other individuals.  In the end, a big guild with many people on at any one time can organize and get to a place faster than a smaller group who needs more time to organize a group.  Therefore, they will always be able to get there first.  Everyone who wants it should have equal access to all of the parts of the game.  To exclude other people because you believe you are better than they are is just plain wrong.<br>
<br>
Someone who is unexperienced at leading a raid should be able to if they want.  If they fail miserably, then people just won't go with them in the future.  If someone who signs up can't get enough support to put together a raid within a reasonable amount of time before it is scheduled to happen, the date should be cleared for someone else.  One of those uber-guilds should have no problem putting together a big enough group for an impromtu raid.<br>
<br>
I realize there are various levels of maturity in the players of this game.  Some people will be blinded by their greed and choose to push for any system that will give them an advantage at the cost of another.  FFA is simply anarchy where the strong can take advantage of the weak.<br>
<br>
I personally have next to no interest in organizing a raid.  It seems tedious and far too much like work than I want to put into a game.  I happily help out raids that my guildies and friends put together and offer any expertise that I can.<br>
<br>
Perhaps instead of clamoring for a system that makes it even more convenient for the powerful guilds to dominate where ever they wish, we should encourage a system that encourages them to help out more individual players and smaller guilds run their own raids.  This is my sentiment for helping out newbies who are putting forth an honest effort, especially those that don't beg...(beggers must be squished!).<br>
<br>
Just my 3 cents in the name of altruism.<br>
